{{onesource|date=November 2018}}
The '''Badawiyyah''', [[Sufi]] [[tariqah|tarika]], was founded in the thirteenth century in [[Egypt]] by [[Ahmad al-Badawi]] (1199-1276). As a tarika, the Badawiyyah lacks any distinct doctrines. <ref name="Ahmadiyyah">{{cite book|last1=el-Aswad|first1=El-Sayed|title=Muslim Worldviews and Everyday Lives|date=July 13, 2012|publisher=Rowman Altamira|isbn=9780759121195|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CnzhXfJfkAMC&pg=PA77&dq=Tanta,+Egypt&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim1ryrk67QAhVMMSYKHXRhCJc4HhDoAQgqMAI#v=onepage&q=Tanta%2C%20Egypt&f=false|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>

It was, however, extremely popular during both [[History of Ottoman Egypt|the Mamluk and Ottoman periods of Egypt]]. [[Mamluk]] Sultans often supported elaborate 'Mawlids' at the resting place of [[Sheikh]] Ahmed al-Badawi (or ''Seyyid Badawi'' as he is more commonly known) in the [[Nile Delta]] town of  [[Tanta]].

During the Ottoman period, this order spread to [[Turkey]] and there were several [[Zawiyya|Tekkes]] or zawiyas in [[Istanbul]] many of which survived until the founding of the Turkish republic.

The mawlid of Seyyid Badawi is still celebrated in Egypt every year where the population of Tanta swells to almost double. Tents are placed in the streets around the [[Mosque]] of Seyyid Badawi where [[Qur'an]] recitations and sermons by important scholars from [[al-Azhar Mosque]] are delivered.

