{{Infobox military structure |name = Jones' Battery |native_name = |partof = [[Fortifications of Gibraltar]] |location =[[Gibraltar]] |image = |caption = |map_type = Gibraltar |map_size = 300 |map_alt = |map_caption = Location in [[Gibraltar]] |type = [[Artillery Battery]] |coordinates = {{coord|36.1433|-5.350|type:landmark_region:GI|display=inline}} |code = |built = |builder = General Sir John Jones |materials = |height = |used = |demolished = |condition = |ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |open_to_public = |controlledby = |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }} '''Jones' Battery''' is one of the best preserved of the "retired" [[artillery battery]] in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]]. It was named after Sir [[John Thomas Jones]] who once controlled the fortifications here.<ref name="Jones1827">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=John Thomas|title=Journals of Sieges Carried on by the Army Under the Duke of Wellington, in Spain, Between the Years 1811 and 1814: With Notes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WvwxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA476|accessdate=29 March 2013|year=1827|publisher=T. Egerton|page=476}}</ref>
==Description== Jones' Battery is close to the [[Moorish Castle]]. It was one of the first set of retired batteries which were proposed by General Sir [[John Thomas Jones|John Jones]]. Jones was an important fortifications expert well respected by military engineers. These "retired" batteries were the first to be set away from the shoreline in order that they could get increased range by taking advantage of the steep slopes of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]]. In addition the batteries location was less obvious to the enemy. Jones also built similar batteries at the Civil Hospital and at [[Raglan's Battery]] overlooking the harbour.<ref name="Finlayson2006">{{cite book|author=Fa & Finlayson|title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&pg=PA32|accessdate=1 April 2013|year=2006|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84603-016-1|pages=32–33}}</ref> In 1859 this battery had eleven guns.<ref name=map1859>{{cite web|title=1859 Map of the Fortifications of Gibraltar|url=http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/78/1859_Gibraltar_fortifications_map.jpg|publisher=UK National Archives MPH 1/23|accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref>
The battery was reportedly well preserved in 2006 as it still had the main wall, expense magazines, parapet and embrasures could be seen just off a road to the ''Moorish Castle Estate''.<ref name="Finlayson55">{{cite book|author=Fa & Finlayson|title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&pg=PA32|accessdate=1 April 2013|year=2006|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84603-016-1|page=55}}</ref>
Jones' idea eventually led to guns being sighted on the very top of the rock.<ref name="Finlayson2006"/>
