{{Moroccan-Portuguese conflicts}}
{{Portuguese colonial campaigns}}
[[File:Portuguese Morocco.PNG|thumb|300px|[[Morocco-Portugal relations|Portuguese possessions in Morocco]] (1415-1769).]]
'''Moroccan–Portuguese conflicts''' refer to a series of battles between [[Morocco]] and [[Portugal]] throughout history. 

The first military conflict, in 21 August 1415, took the form of a [[Conquest of Ceuta|surprise assault on Ceuta]] by the 45,000 Portuguese soldiers who traveled on 200 ships. It was later followed by the [[Siege of Ceuta (1419)|Siege of Ceuta]] in 1419. These events marked the beginning of the decline of the [[Marinid dynasty]] and the start of the [[Portuguese Empire]]. 

The major battle, [[Battle of Alcácer Quibir]], fought at [[Ksar-el-Kebir]] on 4 August 1578, was a catalyst for the [[1580 Portuguese succession crisis]]. This resulted in a [[Iberian Union|dynastic union]] between the [[Kingdom of Portugal]] and the [[Kingdom of Spain]]. 

The conflicts ended when Portugal gave up [[El Jadida|Mazagan]] in 1769.

