{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= }} {{Infobox ship class overview |Name=''Sri Tiga'' class |Builders= [[Boustead Heavy Industries Corporation Berhad|Boustead Naval Shipyard Malaysia]] |Operators={{navy|Malaysia}} |Class before= |Class after= |Subclasses= |Cost= |Built range= |In service range= |Total ships building= |Total ships planned= |Total ships completed=2 |Total ships cancelled= |Total ships active=2 |Total ships laid up= |Total ships lost= |Total ships retired= |Total ships preserved= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Ship type=Fast Troop Vessels |Ship displacement=117 tonnes |Ship length={{convert|38|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship beam={{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship draught={{convert|1.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion=4 MAN D2842 LE 408 diesel, 4 water-jets Hamilton 521 |Ship speed={{convert|28.0|kn}} |Ship capacity= |Ship complement= |Ship sensors= Search and navigation radar Furuno, I-band |Ship EW= |Ship armament=*1x20mm canon |Ship aircraft= |Ship notes= }} |}
The '''''Sri Tiga'' class''' is a class of fast troop vessels of the [[Royal Malaysian Navy]] (RMN) with the length of 38m and displacing 117 tons. A total of two ships are currently in service.
==Development== The Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN) commissioned their two locally built KD Sri Gaya and KD Sri Tiga in 2001.Both ships build by local company [[Boustead Heavy Industries Corporation Berhad|Boustead Naval Shipyard Malaysia]] (BHIC). All ships named after islands in Sabah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://defense-studies.blogspot.my/2011/02/sri-gaya-class-fast-troop-vessel.html?m=1|title=Sri Gaya class : Fast Troop Vessel Angkatan Laut Malaysia|website=defense-studies.blogspot.my|language=id|access-date=2018-04-14}}</ref>
==Characteristics== This ship is made of aluminum, lighter material than steel plate but more secure than fiberglass and needs only minimal maintenance. The crew of this ship is small, leaving more space for carrying troops.
The ship is powered by four waterjets and four machines, able to reach a speed of 25-28 knots. This is high for this size of military troop transport ship. The ship weighs 117 tons and is 38 meters long and 7.2 meters wide. It can carry 32 fully armed troops and equipment at a cruising speed over 1000 km of 14 knots.
For self-defense, this ship is equipped with 20mm cannon. Other weaponry such as grenade launcher and anti-tank guided missile can be added. This ship's modular design allows it to serve multiple purposes, including fast attack, fast troop vessel, light logistic vessel, general cargo, marine ambulance, diving platforms, and patrol.
==Major Operation== In May 2018, the ''KD Sri Tiga'' held a meeting with the [[Philippine Navy]] ship, the [[BRP Cebu (PS-28)|BRP Cebu]] at the maritime border between Malaysia and the [[Philippines]] to exchange intelligence information as part of the ''Trilateral Maritime Patrol Programme'' in the Eastern Security Zone (Esszone) of [[Sabah]].<ref>[http://www.thesundaily.my/news/2018/05/24/msian-filipino-naval-ships-meet-maritime-border-exchange-intelligence "M'sian, Filipino Naval Ships to Meet at Maritime Border to Exchange Intelligence"]</ref>
